<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="133" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,794,1769,2081]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1769,1793]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Redescription</emphasis>
: Species of slender habitus. Body length 5.1–6.0 mm; length of forebody 
<quantity box="[537,666,1801,1825]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="2.7" pageId="16" pageNumber="133" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="2.8" valueMin="2.7">2.7–2.8 mm</quantity>
. Coloration (
<figureCitation box="[196,276,1833,1857]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Figs 22</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[286,314,1833,1857]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">50</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[324,352,1833,1857]" captionStart="Figs 68–81" captionStartId="50.[189,229,2017,2039]" captionTargetBox="[189,1436,239,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-127@50.[189,1436,234,1973]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="Figs 68–81: Forebody (68–77), head and pronotum (78), and abdomen (79–81) of Zyras spp.: brevilobatus (68), parvicollis (69), ambulans (70), nitens, holotype (71), gratellus (Malaysia) (72), matangensis (73), gratellus (Sulawesi) (74), densissimus (75), titan (76), densihirtus (77), nigrihirtus (78), kraatzi (79), asperatus (80), nigroaeneus (81). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742379" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742379/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">81</figureCitation>
): whole body black, forebody with a faint blueish hue; legs bicoloured: femora blackish-brown, tibiae and tarsi pale-yellowish; antennae blackish-brown with antennomeres I–II and the base of III yellowish; maxillary palpi brown, with the terminal palpomere yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,794,1769,2081]" lastBlockId="16.[831,1437,233,1633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[266,341,2025,2049]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) moderately transverse, median portion extensively impunctate; punctures in lateral portions sparse and coarse. Eyes longer than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[1105,1179,265,289]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity box="[1355,1437,265,289]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="16" pageNumber="133" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
long and moderately slender; antennomeres IV–V approximately as long as broad, VI–X increasingly transverse and of gradually increasing width, X approximately 1.5 times as broad as long, and XI barely as long as the combined length of IX and X.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,233,1633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[957,1032,457,481]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.1 times as broad as long and approximately 1.25 times as broad as head, not distinctly tapering posteriad, broadest approximately in the middle; lateral margins weakly convex in dorsal view; punctation coarse, sparse, and very irregularly distributed, with rather large impunctate areas on either side of midline; midline broadly impunctate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,233,1633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[916,991,681,705]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) 0.86–0.93 times as long as pronotum; punctation moderately coarse, defined, rather sparse, and regularly distributed; interstices on average approximately three times as broad as diameter of punctures. Hind wings fully developed. Metatarsomere I shorter than the combined length of II–IV.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,233,1633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[951,1025,873,897]" captionStart="Figs 68–81" captionStartId="50.[189,229,2017,2039]" captionTargetBox="[189,1436,239,1959]" captionTargetId="figure-127@50.[189,1436,234,1973]" captionTargetPageId="50" captionText="Figs 68–81: Forebody (68–77), head and pronotum (78), and abdomen (79–81) of Zyras spp.: brevilobatus (68), parvicollis (69), ambulans (70), nitens, holotype (71), gratellus (Malaysia) (72), matangensis (73), gratellus (Sulawesi) (74), densissimus (75), titan (76), densihirtus (77), nigrihirtus (78), kraatzi (79), asperatus (80), nigroaeneus (81). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742379" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742379/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
) narrower than elytra, gradually tapering from base to apex, with sharp paratergites; anterior impressions on tergites III–V rather shallow; anterior impressions of tergites III–V each with a transverse row of sparse and fine non-setiferous punctures; tergites III–IV with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side and with four setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite V with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side and with six setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite VI with a transverse row of non-setiferous punctures anteriorly, with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side, with a median pair of setiferous punctures in posterior portion, and with six setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite VII with a transverse band of sparse and fine non-setiferous punctures anteriorly and with scattered setiferous punctures in posterior portion, posterior margin with palisade fringe; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1285,1372,1385,1409]" captionStart="Figs 134–155" captionStartId="56.[189,229,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[193,1432,245,1957]" captionTargetId="figure-136@56.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 134–155: Zyras perforatus (134–135), Z. pallipes (136–139), Z. nigroaeneus, holotype (140–141), Z. condignus (142–147), Z. morvani, holotype (148–149), and Z. truncatus (150–155): male tergite VIII (134, 138, 140, 146, 148, 152); male sternite VIII (135, 139, 141, 147, 149, 153); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (136–137, 142–143, 150–151); paramere (144–145); female tergite VIII (154); female sternite VIII (155). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888366" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888366/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Fig. 140</figureCitation>
) with sparse setiferous punctures only in posterior portion, posterior margin convex and with distinct concavity in the middle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,233,1633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
♂: sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1011,1099,1513,1537]" captionStart="Figs 134–155" captionStartId="56.[189,229,1989,2011]" captionTargetBox="[193,1432,245,1957]" captionTargetId="figure-136@56.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 134–155: Zyras perforatus (134–135), Z. pallipes (136–139), Z. nigroaeneus, holotype (140–141), Z. condignus (142–147), Z. morvani, holotype (148–149), and Z. truncatus (150–155): male tergite VIII (134, 138, 140, 146, 148, 152); male sternite VIII (135, 139, 141, 147, 149, 153); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (136–137, 142–143, 150–151); paramere (144–145); female tergite VIII (154); female sternite VIII (155). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888366" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888366/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Fig. 141</figureCitation>
) much longer than tergite VIII, posteriorly strongly convex; aedeagus not available.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,233,1633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">♀: posterior margin of sternite VIII shallowly concave in the middle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[832,1436,1673,1825]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[832,1050,1673,1697]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: Among its geographically close congeners, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[959,1112,1706,1729]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigroaeneus">
<emphasis box="[959,1112,1706,1729]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Z. nigroaeneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized particularly by its slender habitus, the conspicuous coloration of the body and the legs, and by the punctation pattern of the abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="133" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[832,1436,1865,2017]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[832,1229,1865,1889]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Distribution and natural history</emphasis>
: This species is currently known only from its type locality in 
<collectingRegion country="India" name="Himachal Pradesh" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Himachal Pradesh</collectingRegion>
and from one locality in 
<collectingRegion box="[1205,1358,1929,1953]" country="India" name="Uttar Pradesh" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Uttar Pradesh</collectingRegion>
, North 
<collectingCountry box="[832,888,1961,1985]" name="India" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[901,972,1961,1985]" captionStart="Map 2" captionStartId="64.[189,234,1456,1477]" captionTargetBox="[189,1436,891,1446]" captionTargetId="figure-96@64.[189,1436,891,1446]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Map 2: Revised distributions of Zyras pindarae (black circles) and Z. nigroaeneus (white circles) in the Himalaya." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742395/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">Map 2</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus box="[1038,1120,1962,1986]" pageId="16" pageNumber="133">syntype</typeStatus>
was collected at an altitude of approximately 
<quantity box="[990,1071,1993,2017]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="16" pageNumber="133" unit="m" value="2800.0">2800 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
